\begin_layout Standard
For a two-dimensional system, we could easily solve the problem of reducing
 the full unit-norm space to its irreducible components 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hat{a}=\left(X,Y,Z\right)$
\end_inset

 characterizing the Bloch sphere.
 We have just argued that essentially the same process is possible for 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional system: in the abstract argument, we simply identify the family
 of coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 as being the same if they differ only by an overall phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\rme^{\rmi\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 However, in practice this is not a construction that is easy to realize
 in a practical computation.
 We now outline an explicit algorithm for accomplishing the reduction to
 the irreducible 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional state space 
\begin_inset Formula $\CP{D-1}$
\end_inset

; this construction will turn out to be useful for the validation of our
 discrete results to follow below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a normalized pure state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\alpha_{i}\ket{i}$
\end_inset

, a natural quantity characterizing an 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional system is its 
\shape italic
density matrix
\shape default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\op{\Psi}{\Psi}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\begin{pmatrix}|\alpha_{0}|^{2} & \alpha_{0}\alpha_{1}^{*} & \cdots & \alpha_{0}\alpha_{D-1}^{*}\\
\alpha_{1}\alpha_{0}^{*} & |\alpha_{1}|^{2} & \cdots & \alpha_{1}\alpha_{D-1}^{*}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\alpha_{D-1}\alpha_{0}^{*} & \cdots & \alpha_{D-1}\alpha_{D-2}^{*} & |\alpha_{D-1}|^{2}
\end{pmatrix}\,.\label{nqDensity.eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can now use the complex generalization of the classical Veronese coordinate
 system for projective geometry to remove the overall phase ambiguity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rme^{\rmi\theta}$
\end_inset

 from the 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

-dimensional states.
 If we take a particular weighting of the elements of the density matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, we can construct a 
\shape italic
unit vector
\shape default
 of real dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}$
\end_inset

 with the form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Hat{a}=\left(|\alpha_{i}|^{2},\ldots,\sqrt{2}\,\mathrm{Re}\ \alpha_{i}\alpha_{j}^{*},\ldots,\sqrt{2}\,\mathrm{Im}\ \alpha_{i}\alpha_{j}^{*},\ldots\right)\,,\label{nqCoords.eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Hat{a}\cdot\Hat{a}=\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\left(\left|\alpha_{i}\right|^{2}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\sum_{\substack{j=0\\
j\ne i
}
}^{D-1}\left(\mathrm{Re}\ \alpha_{i}\alpha_{j}^{*}\right)^{2}+\left(\mathrm{Im}\ \alpha_{i}\alpha_{j}^{*}\right)^{2}=\left(\sum_{i=0}^{D-1}\left|\alpha_{i}\right|^{2}\right)\left(\sum_{j=0}^{D-1}\left|\alpha_{j}\right|^{2}\right)=1\,.
\]

\end_inset

This construction gives an explicit embedding of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(D-1\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional complex, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2D-2\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional real, object in a real space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 However, this is somewhat subtle because the vector is of unit length,
 so technically the embedding space is a sphere of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{2}-1$
\end_inset

 embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{D^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the two-dimensional irreducible states could be represented
 in a four-dimensional embedding, but the magnitude of every coordinate
 would be one; furthermore, the object embedded in the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{3}$
\end_inset

 is indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2}$
\end_inset

 because we can fix one complex coordinate to be unity, and let one vary,
 giving a total of two irreducible dimensions.
 In fact one must choose 
\shape italic
two
\shape default
 coordinate patches, one covering one pole of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2}$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}=1+\rmi0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=x_{1}+\rmi y_{1}$
\end_inset

, and the other patch covering the other pole of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sphere{2}$
\end_inset

 with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}=x_{0}+\rmi y_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=1+\rmi0$
\end_inset

.
 
